155.3	Daniel_Ellsberg	Daniel Ellsberg	Daniel Ellsberg, PhD, (born April 7, 1931) is a former United States military analyst who, while employed by the RAND Corporation, precipitated a national political controversy in 1971 when he released the Pentagon Papers, a top-secret Pentagon study of U.S. government decision-making in relation to the Vietnam War, to The New York Times and other newspapers. He was awarded the Right Livelihood Award in 2006. He is also known for a fundamental contribution to decision theory, the Ellsberg paradox.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Daniel_Ellsberg_2006.jpg/220px-Daniel_Ellsberg_2006.jpg
